Merging audio

pkg install ffmpeg


ffmpeg -f concat -safe 0 -i <(for f in *.mp3; do echo "file '$PWD/$f'"; done) -c copy "merged_output.mp3"


Just enter the folder using cd and rewrite the name of the output as you want

Trimming audio 

pkg install ffmpeg


ffmpeg -i "input.mp3"  -ss 00:00:30 -t 00:00:10 -c copy "output.mp3" 


00:00:30 initial time
00:00:10 time period of trim


Increase the volume


ffmpeg -i "input.mp3" -filter:a "volume=2.0" "louder_audio.mp3"
 

Volume=2.0 change 2.0 to the speed you want 


Increase pitchness

ffmpeg -i "input.mp3" -filter:a "asetrate=44100*1.5,aresample=44100" "high_pitch.mp3"


Increase speed 


ffmpeg -i "input.mp3" -filter:a "atempo=2.0" -vn "fast_audio.mp3"


Change 2.0 for different speed


Silencer

ffmpeg -i "input.mp3" -filter_complex \
"anullsrc=r=44100:cl=stereo:d=5[silence]; \
[0:a]atrim=end=10[part1]; \
[0:a]atrim=start=10[part2]; \
[part1][silence][part2]concat=n=3:v=0:a=1" \
"output.mp3"

The Gap Duration (d=5): Inside the anullsrc section, change 5 to the number of seconds of silence you want to insert.

The Split Point (end=10 and start=10): This is the "timestamp" where the silence will be injected. Change 10 to the second mark where you want the gap to appear.

Note: Both numbers must be the same so the audio isn't cut or repeated.

When Audio is too early (Delay Audio)

ffmpeg -i "input.mp4" -itsoffset 10.0 -i "input.mp4" -map 0:v -map 1:a -c:v copy -c:a aac "output_fixed.mp4"

In place of 10.0 put the delayed time period and replace input.mp4by filename


